Super Shades: 15 Best New Car Colors Of 2019

Greens and blues and oranges and yellows.

Slideshow
1 / 17
2 / 17

Ametrin Metallic: BMW

The BMW Individual color Ametrin Metallic debuted on the X7 in September. But it wasn't until the all-new M8 Gran Coupe adorned the purple-ish hue later in the year did people take notice. The deep shade draped atop the sleek lines of the 600-horsepower four-door do the M8 Gran Coupe serious justice. Though if you really want it, it's a $1,950 option.

Read Our BMW 8 Series Review:

2019 BMW M850i xDrive Review: Big Speed, Little Character
3 / 17

Army Green: Toyota

Not only did the TRD Pro lineup (which includes the Tacoma, Tundra, 4Runner, and Sequoia) get updates in tech and styling for 2020, but Toyota also gave the range a fresh paint job. Army Green joins three alternatives on the TRD Pro color wheel, is available as a no-cost option, and makes Toyota's mightiest products look that much cooler.

Read Our Toyota TRD Pro Reviews:

2020 Toyota Sequoia TRD Pro First Drive: Adventure, Party Of Seven
Like A Pro: Ranking The 2020 Toyota TRD Pro Models Off-Road
4 / 17

Dark Moss: Kia

The Kia Telluride's rugged styling looks even better with the Dark Moss paint job. New for 2019, Kia offers Dark Moss as a no-cost option atop the three-row Telluride exclusively. The smaller Soul wears a similar Undercover Green paint, but it doesn't have the same hue as the Telluride's darker green finish.

Read Our Kia Telluride Reviews:

2020 Kia Telluride SX Review: Dare To Be Different
2020 Kia Telluride SX First Drive: Telluridin Dirty
5 / 17

Deep Garnet: Lexus

The Lexus LS looks absolutely tantalizing with the new-for-2019 Deep Garnet finish, especially over the 20-inch Black Vapor chrome wheels. Unfortunately, Lexus limits the color combo to the limited LS 500 Inspiration Series, available exclusively with the 3.5-liter twin-turbo V6 and capped at just 300 units in the U.S. Here's hoping Lexus expands Deep Garnet to more vehicles (read: LC).

Read Our Lexus LS Reviews:

2019 Lexus LS 500 F Sport Driving Notes: Large, Not In Charge
2018 Lexus LS 500 | Why Buy?
6 / 17

Downshift Blue: Toyota

The new Toyota Supra comes in a few good colors. But our favorite is Downshift Blue. While bright hues like Nitro Yellow and Renaissance Red get all the love from fans, the more-subdued Downshift Blue finish feels like a mature option for a car that's fun as hell, no matter the shade.

Read Our Toyota Supra Review:

2020 Toyota Supra First Drive: Dont Call It A Comeback
7 / 17

Frozen Blue: Porsche

Frozen Blue is an apt description of the new color for the Porsche Taycan 4Saycan. Especially considering we drove this exact car in arctic temperatures. But in any climate, the subtle shade does Porsche's first electric vehicle justice and feels less shouty than some of the colors on this list.

Read Our Porsche Taycan 4S Reviews:

Taking The Porsche Taycan 4S Ice Driving In The Arctic Circle
2020 Porsche Taycan 4S First Drive: Canyon Carver, Winter Warrior
8 / 17

Fux Orange: Rolls-Royce

Admittedly, Fux Orange is a one-off color commissioned by known collector, Michael Fux. So, the company doesn't offer it through traditional buying channels. But who cares, the bright citrus hue looks awesome on the opulent Cullinan SUV. And knowing Rolls-Royce, you can probably get this bespoke color on your car, too... if you have the cash.

Read Our Rolls-Royce Cullinan Reviews:

2019 Rolls-Royce Cullinan Review: High On Ecstasy
2020 Rolls-Royce Cullinan Black Badge First Drive: Dark Horse
9 / 17

Grabber Lime: Ford

The Mustang Shelby GT500 has such an amazing selection of colors, it's hard to choose just one. But the consensus is that Grabber Lime is the most for lack of a better word grabbing. The bright green hue does a great job showing off GT500's sharp cues. It's even better when paired with white racing stripes and carbon fiber trim pieces.

Read Our Ford Mustang Reviews:

2020 Ford Mustang Shelby GT500 First Drive: Pony Excess
2021 Ford Mustang Mach-E First Ride: An Electrifying Start
10 / 17

Hakone Green: Toyota

The only way to get a Toyota 86 with Hakone Green is by selecting the limited Hakone Edition package, which also comes paired to perfect 17-inch bronze wheels. That'll cost you $29,630 (or $30,350 with the six-speed automatic). But hurry, the company only has a few hundred examples of the Hakone Edition model in the U.S.

Read Our Toyota 86 Reviews:

2020 Toyota 86 TRD Handling Package First Drive: Almost Perfect
2019 Toyota 86 GT: Pros And Cons
11 / 17

Ice: Bentley

If there's any color as aptly named as Bentley's Ice, we haven't heard of it. Introduced this year, the subtle yet stylish hue looks superb atop the new Flying Spur especially when optioned with the 21-inch black Mulliner wheels and Blackline trim package.

Read Our Bentley Flying Spur Review:

2020 Bentley Flying Spur First Drive: Pinky-Up Powerhouse
12 / 17

Indy Yellow Pearl: Acura

To keep the NSX fresh, Acura this year unveiled a few fantastic new colors. Indy Yellow Pearl and Thermal Orange join the lineup for 2019, and both are a $1,000 option. But while many other automakers do orange well, Acura is one of the few with a really great yellow paint option. It's one of our favorites.

Read Our Acura NSX Reviews:

2019 Acura NSX First Drive: One Foot Out Of The Shadows
2019 Acura NSX Review: NSX And Candy
13 / 17

Performance Blue: Hyundai

The Hyundai Veloster N is one of the best hot hatchbacks of the year. It's even better when wearing its signature Performance Blue paint job, one of four available hues for the 2020 model year. That subtle paint pairs to red accents and a carbon fiber wing, giving the Veloster N the sporty look it deserves.

Read Our Hyundai Veloster N Reviews:

2019 Hyundai Veloster N: Pros And Cons
2019 Hyundai Veloster N First Drive: Taking It To The Nth
14 / 17

Petra Gold: Rolls-Royce

Like Fux Orange, Rolls-Royce introduced its bespoke Petra Gold paint job on a one-off Cullinan at a dealership in Abu Dhabi. But the company should probably consider offering it as a standard option it's stunning. Atop the posh SUV the rose gold-like hue shines, making the Cullinan look even more imposing.

More Future Cars:

Super Shades: 20 Best New Car Colors Of 2020
15 Future Cars Worth Waiting For
15 / 17

Radium Green: Bentley

This year Bentley celebrated a Pikes Peak Hill Climb record the only way the company knows how: with a gorgeous, special edition Continental GT. Limited to just 15 examples, the custom Conti wears a brand-new Radium Green paint job and an optional "100" logo in the grille celebrating the brand's centenary year.

Read Our Bentley Continental GT Review:

2020 Bentley Continental GT V8 First Drive: A True Bentley
16 / 17

Shock: Chevrolet

The Camaro gets a new highlighter hue dubbed Shock for the 2020 model year. The first time Chevy showed the color was in July, promising a limited run for Russia. But now the color is a $395 option on any 2020 Camaro. It definitely stands out.

15 Future Cars Worth Waiting For
Dec 20, 2019 at 9:44am ET
3
By: Jeff Perez
Listen to this article

According to a 2019 study, the most popular car colors are white, black, and grey in that order. The trio makes up 70 percent of colors on all new vehicles sold. But why? This year, brands like Acura, Chevrolet, Toyota, and plenty others released exciting new paint jobs. Each one of these unique colors offering customers an escape from the ordinary. Whether you want an Indy Yellow NSX, a Frozen Blue Taycan 4S, or an Army Green Tacoma TRD Pro, there's no shortage of exciting hues to choose from. These are just 15 of our favorites, in particular order.
